                <head>400. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>At a meeting of the National Security Council on September 25, 1968,
                    Representative to the United Nations <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">George W.
                        Ball</persName> briefly reviewed issues likely to arise at the forthcoming
                    meeting of the U.N. General Assembly. Notes of the meeting prepared by W. Thomas
                    Johnson of the White House staff record <persName corresp="#p_BGW1"
                        >Ball</persName>’s comments under the heading of “Biafra” as follows: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Hardships and suffering are enormous.</p>
                        <p>“Both sides are willing to sacrifice millions of lives to win political
                            position.</p>
                        <p>“Very little food getting in.</p>
                        <p>“Africans do not want the U.N. in on it—they say it’s an African
                            problem.</p>
                        <p>“I propose the President designate somebody to deal with humanitarian
                            problems.</p>
                        <p>“There is great pressure to do something on it. We must help the <gloss
                                target="#t_ICRC1">ICRC</gloss> and other international
                            agencies.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>There was no further discussion concerning Nigeria. (Johnson Library, Tom
                    Johnson’s Notes of Meetings, September 25, 1968, National Security Council)</p>
            </div>
